Note: ================================================================
Note: Makefile Translation Test Suite
Note: ================================================================
Note: Comprehensive tests for Makefile bidirectional translation.
Note: Drives the real Makefile translation pipeline end to end:
Note:   - Lexer: create_lexer + tokenize (source -> token stream)
Note:   - Parser: create_parser + parse_makefile (tokens -> AST)
Note:   - HIR: makefile_to_hir_from_source (source -> HIR)
Note:   - Backend: create_backend + translate_hir_module (HIR -> Makefile)
Note:   - Round-trip: emitter parse_makefile + generate_makefile
Note: ================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/makefile/makefile_lexer.runa" as MakefileLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/makefile/makefile_parser.runa" as MakefileParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/makefile/makefile_to_hir.runa" as MakefileToHIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/makefile/hir_to_makefile.runa" as HIRToMakefile
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/makefile/makefile_emitter.runa" as MakefileEmitter
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

@Reasoning:
Three-counter aggregate for the Makefile pipeline driver. The shared
results handle threads through every test_* proc so the final verdict
reflects all phases.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
total at offset 0, passed at 8, failed at 16, maintained through
type-checked field access on the value-typed SuiteResults.
@End Implementation

Type called "SuiteResults":
    total as Integer
    passed as Integer
    failed as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Top-level orchestrator. Runs the lexer, parser, HIR, backend, and
round-trip phases against the real translation entry points and
prints a final pass/fail summary. Returns non-zero if any test
failed so a build runner can gate on the exit code.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Initialize SuiteResults, print header, call each test_* proc passing
the shared results handle, print summary, return 1 when
results.failed > 0 else 0.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All phases pass -> failed == 0, exit 0
- Any assertion fails -> failed >= 1, exit 1
@End TestCases

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be a value of type SuiteResults with
        total as 0,
        passed as 0,
        failed as 0

    proc print_main_header

    proc test_lexer with results
    proc test_parser with results
    proc test_to_hir with results
    proc test_backend with results
    proc test_round_trip with results

    proc print_final_results with results

    If results.failed is greater than 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lexer phase: verifies create_lexer + tokenize produce a non-zero
token-stream handle for representative Makefile inputs (variable
assignment, rule with recipe).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two lex+record blocks. Each creates a lexer over the source, runs
tokenize, and records a pass when the returned tokens handle is
non-zero.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "CC = gcc\n" -> tokens != 0
- "all:\n\techo hi\n" -> tokens != 0
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    proc print_string with "Testing Makefile lexer..."
    proc print_newline

    Let src1 be proc create_string_literal with "CC = gcc\n"
    Let lexer1 be proc create_lexer from MakefileLexer with src1
    Let tokens1 be proc tokenize from MakefileLexer with lexer1
    proc record_nonzero with results, tokens1, "Lex variable assignment"

    Let src2 be proc create_string_literal with "all:\n\techo hi\n"
    Let lexer2 be proc create_lexer from MakefileLexer with src2
    Let tokens2 be proc tokenize from MakefileLexer with lexer2
    proc record_nonzero with results, tokens2, "Lex rule with recipe"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parser phase: drives the real lex -> create_parser -> parse_makefile
chain and verifies a non-zero AST handle for a variable assignment
and a target rule.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two blocks. Each tokenizes the source, builds a parser over the
tokens, parses the Makefile, and records a pass when the AST handle
is non-zero.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "CFLAGS = -O2\n" -> AST != 0
- "build: main.o\n\tcc -o build main.o\n" -> AST != 0
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    proc print_string with "Testing Makefile parser..."
    proc print_newline

    Let src1 be proc create_string_literal with "CFLAGS = -O2\n"
    Let lexer1 be proc create_lexer from MakefileLexer with src1
    Let tokens1 be proc tokenize from MakefileLexer with lexer1
    Let parser1 be proc create_parser from MakefileParser with tokens1
    Let ast1 be proc parse_makefile from MakefileParser with parser1
    proc record_nonzero with results, ast1, "Parse variable assignment"

    Let src2 be proc create_string_literal with "build: main.o\n\tcc -o build main.o\n"
    Let lexer2 be proc create_lexer from MakefileLexer with src2
    Let tokens2 be proc tokenize from MakefileLexer with lexer2
    Let parser2 be proc create_parser from MakefileParser with tokens2
    Let ast2 be proc parse_makefile from MakefileParser with parser2
    proc record_nonzero with results, ast2, "Parse target rule"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR phase: verifies makefile_to_hir_from_source lowers source all the
way to a non-zero HIR handle, proving lex+parse+translate chains
correctly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two source-to-HIR blocks. Each records a pass when the returned HIR
handle is non-zero.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "PREFIX = /usr/local\n" -> HIR != 0
- "clean:\n\trm -f *.o\n" -> HIR != 0
@End TestCases

Process called "test_to_hir" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    proc print_string with "Testing Makefile to HIR translation..."
    proc print_newline

    Let src1 be proc create_string_literal with "PREFIX = /usr/local\n"
    Let hir1 be proc makefile_to_hir_from_source from MakefileToHIR with src1
    proc record_nonzero with results, hir1, "HIR from variable assignment"

    Let src2 be proc create_string_literal with "clean:\n\trm -f *.o\n"
    Let hir2 be proc makefile_to_hir_from_source from MakefileToHIR with src2
    proc record_nonzero with results, hir2, "HIR from clean rule"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Backend phase: lowers source to HIR, emits Makefile text via the
HIR-to-Makefile backend (create_backend + translate_hir_module),
and asserts the emitted text contains the salient identifier.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. makefile_to_hir_from_source -> hir.
2. create_backend -> backend.
3. translate_hir_module(backend, hir) -> output.
4. string_contains assertion on the output.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "CC = gcc\n" -> output contains "CC"
- Backend drops the variable name -> "Backend emits variable name" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_backend" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    proc print_string with "Testing HIR to Makefile generation..."
    proc print_newline

    Let src be proc create_string_literal with "CC = gcc\n"
    Let hir be proc makefile_to_hir_from_source from MakefileToHIR with src

    Let backend be proc create_backend from HIRToMakefile
    Let output be proc translate_hir_module from HIRToMakefile with backend, hir

    Let cc_needle be proc create_string_literal with "CC"
    Let has_cc be proc string_contains with output, cc_needle
    proc record_equals with results, has_cc, 1, "Backend emits variable name"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Round-trip phase: Makefile -> HIR -> Makefile via the emitter facade.
parse_makefile lowers the source to HIR inside the emitter, and
generate_makefile emits the regenerated Makefile text. The salient
tokens must survive both directions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. create_emitter -> emitter.
2. parse_makefile(emitter, source) -> hir.
3. generate_makefile(emitter) -> output.
4. string_contains for the variable name and its value.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "TARGET = app\n" -> output contains "TARGET" and "app"
- Emitter drops the value -> "Round-trip preserves value" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_round_trip" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    proc print_string with "Testing Makefile round-trip..."
    proc print_newline

    Let src be proc create_string_literal with "TARGET = app\n"
    Let emitter be proc create_emitter from MakefileEmitter
    Let hir be proc parse_makefile from MakefileEmitter with emitter, src
    proc record_nonzero with results, hir, "Round-trip parse to HIR"

    Let output be proc generate_makefile from MakefileEmitter with emitter

    Let target_needle be proc create_string_literal with "TARGET"
    Let has_target be proc string_contains with output, target_needle
    proc record_equals with results, has_target, 1, "Round-trip preserves name"

    Let app_needle be proc create_string_literal with "app"
    Let has_app be proc string_contains with output, app_needle
    proc record_equals with results, has_app, 1, "Round-trip preserves value"

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Recording / assertion helpers
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Records a pass when value is non-zero (used for token/AST/HIR handle
presence checks). Increments total always and passed/failed based on
the handle, printing a localized failure line on miss.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
results.total += 1. If value != 0, results.passed += 1; otherwise
results.failed += 1 and print "FAILED: <message> (null handle)".
@End Implementation

Process called "record_nonzero" takes results as Integer, value as Integer, message as String returns Integer:
    Set results.total to results.total plus 1

    If value is not equal to 0:
        Set results.passed to results.passed plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Set results.failed to results.failed plus 1
        proc print_string with "FAILED: "
        proc print_string with message
        proc print_string with " (null handle)"
        proc print_newline
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records a pass when actual equals expected (used for contains
checks). Increments total always and passed/failed accordingly,
printing both operands on a miss for fast localization.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
results.total += 1. If actual == expected, results.passed += 1;
otherwise results.failed += 1 and print the message plus operands.
@End Implementation

Process called "record_equals" takes results as Integer, actual as Integer, expected as Integer, message as String returns Integer:
    Set results.total to results.total plus 1

    If actual is equal to expected:
        Set results.passed to results.passed plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Set results.failed to results.failed plus 1
        proc print_string with "FAILED: "
        proc print_string with message
        proc print_string with " (expected: "
        proc print_integer with expected
        proc print_string with ", actual: "
        proc print_integer with actual
        proc print_string with ")"
        proc print_newline
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Output helpers
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Banner emitted once at startup naming the suite and the five pipeline
phases it drives.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print title, separator, and a one-line description of the covered
phases.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_main_header" returns Integer:
    proc print_string with "MAKEFILE TRANSLATION TEST SUITE"
    proc print_newline
    proc print_string with "===================================="
    proc print_newline
    proc print_string with "Lexer / Parser / HIR / Backend / Round-Trip"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Final summary. Prints the total/passed/failed counts via type-checked
field access and a single human-readable verdict line.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print separator and three counter lines. If results.failed == 0 print
"ALL TESTS PASSED!" else "SOME TESTS FAILED!".
@End Implementation

Process called "print_final_results" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    proc print_string with "===================================="
    proc print_newline

    proc print_string with "Total: "
    proc print_integer with results.total
    proc print_newline

    proc print_string with "Passed: "
    proc print_integer with results.passed
    proc print_newline

    proc print_string with "Failed: "
    proc print_integer with results.failed
    proc print_newline

    If results.failed is equal to 0:
        proc print_string with "ALL TESTS PASSED!"
        proc print_newline
    Otherwise:
        proc print_string with "SOME TESTS FAILED!"
        proc print_newline
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: String helpers
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Naive substring search used by backend and round-trip tests to verify
Makefile tokens survive translation. Operates on the null-terminated
C strings produced by the backend and emitter.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
A zero (null) haystack -> 0. Empty needle -> 1. needle longer than
haystack -> 0. Slide a window over haystack; if all needle bytes
match at any position -> 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_contains" takes haystack as Integer, needle as Integer returns Integer:
    If haystack is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let haystack_len be proc string_length from StringCore with haystack
    Let needle_len be proc string_length from StringCore with needle

    If needle_len is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    If needle_len is greater than haystack_len:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    Let max_i be haystack_len minus needle_len

    While i is less than or equal to max_i:
        Let matches be 1
        Let j be 0

        While j is less than needle_len:
            Let h_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with haystack, i plus j
            Let n_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with needle, j

            If h_char is not equal to n_char:
                Set matches to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Thin wrapper around StringCore.create_from_literal so call sites read
as "create_string_literal" without a hard dependency on the exact
primitive name.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forward to StringCore.create_from_literal(value).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_string_literal" takes value as String returns Integer:
    Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with value
End Process

Note: print_string, print_newline, and print_integer are bootstrap-runtime
Note: globals; test code calls them directly.
